Here's the registration setup:

```csharp
public static class MauiProgram
{
    public static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()
    {
        var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();
        builder.UseMauiApp<App>();

        // One HttpClient + data service for the entire app
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<HttpClient>();
        builder.Services.AddSingleton<IDataService, DataService>();

        // New ViewModel instance per navigation to avoid stale state
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainViewModel>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailViewModel>();

        // New page instance per navigation (owns its ViewModel)
        builder.Services.AddTransient<MainPage>();
        builder.Services.AddTransient<DetailPage>();

        return builder.Build();
    }
}
```

**Why these lifetimes:**

| Registration | Lifetime | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `HttpClient` | **Singleton** | Reuse connections; avoid socket exhaustion |
| `IDataService` | **Singleton** | Stateless API wrapper — one instance serves all consumers, shares the single `HttpClient` |
| ViewModels | **Transient** | Each navigation gets fresh state (selected item, form fields, etc.). A singleton VM would leak state between visits |
| Pages | **Transient** | Pages hold UI state and bind to their ViewModel. A fresh page per navigation avoids visual artifacts and stale bindings |

**Key rule of thumb:** services that hold no per-request state → **singleton**. Anything tied to a screen or user interaction → **transient**. You'd use **scoped** in MAUI only if you define custom scopes (rare — it's more common in ASP.NET).
